The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 A woman has alleged that she was molested by the conductor of a private bus on APC Road. The incident occurred on September 16 and the woman lodged a complaint with Amherst Street police station the same day. An officer of the police station said on Sunday that the woman, a resident of Sukeas Street, boarded the Sealdah-bound bus from a stop close to her house. 

 On reaching her destination, she wanted to get off, but the bus did not stop. She was standing on the footboard, when the conductor allegedly molested her. She got down at the next stop and lodged the police complaint.

 Six people were seriously injured early on Sunday when the car they were travelling in from a city discotheque met with an accident in Dankuni, Hooghly. Police said Kuheli Das, Somnath Bhattacharya, Partha Kabi and Prithwiraj Bhattacharya were travelling in the car, which was being driven by Anil Singh. The car overturned after hitting a police jeep and then a signal post. All five were admitted to a nursing home in Salt Lake. 

 The body of an unidentified man, aged around 40, was found beside the railway tracks between Tikiapara and Dasnagar stations, in Howrah, on Sunday morning. There were injury marks in the head and the torso was bare. A nylon cord and a green shirt were found beside the body. A ticket for Mumbai Mail, dated September 15, was found in one of the pockets of the man?s trousers, a Government Railway Police officer said. An inquiry has been ordered.

 The city police, along with taxi unions, will set up a prepaid taxi booth at Sealdah station. The booth is likely to be inaugurated on November 1, officials said on Sunday. The move is part of the celebrations of the 150 years of the city force. 

 Classes will resume at West Bengal University of Technology from Monday. Officials said the impasse on campus was sorted out on Saturday after talks between the authorities and students? unions. The university was closed on September 13 for an indefinite period after students, who failed in the regular examination and were denied promotion, demanded that they be allowed to sit for supplementary tests.

 The condition of 40 injured passengers of the bus, which broke through the railing of a bridge and fell on the railway tracks at Bally Halt station, was improving, hospital sources said on Sunday. The injured were admitted to Calcutta Medical College and Hospital. Two of them were released on Sunday.

 Calcutta University has set up a satellite antenna, which will connect the institution with those in other metros for e-learning programmes. Work is on for setting up a giant screen in the Centenary Hall to enable video conferencing with colleges and universities in other cities.

 Forty-four dengue cases were diagnosed by civic clinics on Sunday. Mayor Bikash Ranjan Bhattacharya, however, said dengue was declining in the city.

 M.K. Biswas, officer-in-charge of South Port police station, was injured on Gwalior Ghat Road on Sunday evening after being hit by a speeding two-wheeler. He was crossing the road when the mishap occurred. He was admitted to Calcutta Medical Research Institute.

